<subsection xml:id="subsection-standard-normal-distn">
   <title>The Standard Normal Distribution:</title>
      <p>
        Recall that the <m>z</m>-score of a value, <m>x</m>, describes the number of standard deviations that the value <m>x</m> is from the mean of its distribution:
        <me>z=\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}</me>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Values of <m>x</m> that are less than the mean have _______ <m>z</m>-scores
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Values of <m>x</m> that are more than the mean have _______ <m>z</m>-scores
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <m>z</m>-score for the mean equals ________
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        </p>

        <exercise>
           <statement>
            A coffee shop wants to understand the distribution of amounts that their customers are spending per order.  They find that the average amount a customer spends per order is <m>\$ 7.50</m>, and the standard deviation is <m>\$1.25</m>.  If we assume that the amounts spent per order are normally distributed, and Rey comes in and spends <m>\$10.00</m>, what is the <m>z</m>-score for Rey's order?
        </statement>
        </exercise>


        <definition xml:id="def-standard-normal">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    When the original random variable, <m>x</m>, follows a normal distribution, <m>z</m>-scores also follow a normal distribution with <m>\mu=0</m>, <m>\sigma=1</m>.  It is called the <em>standard normal distribution</em>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>


        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of Standard Normal Distribution powered by Desmos</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="desmos-standard-normal" desmos="elacje4bcl" aspect="4:3" />
          </figure>

          <p>
            The standard normal distribution allows us to calculate probabilities for any normal distribution since we can standardize it with <m>z</m>-scores.   Tables ??????? provide you with the cumulative area to the LEFT of the <m>z</m>-score.  We can also use Excel to calculate the cumulative area to the left of the <m>z</m>-score by typing 
            <me>=NORM.S.DIST(x,TRUE)</me>
          </p>

          <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
            Find the probability <m>P(Z\leq -1.3)</m> for a standard normal distribution
                </p>
            </statement>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    In Excel:  <m>=NORM.S.DIST(-1.3,TRUE)\approx 0.0968 </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
          </example>

          <p>
            So how do we use the table or the Excel formula to find any probability for a normal distribution?
          </p>

          <p>
            There are 3 basic types of problems:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To the left of any <m>z</m>-score:  Look up the <m>z</m>-score in the table (or calculate it in Excel) and use the area given.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To the right of any <m>z</m>-score:  Look up the <m>z</m>-score in the table (or calculate it in Excel) subtract the area from 1.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Between any two <m>z</m>-scores:  Look up both <m>z</m>-scores in the table (or calculate them in Excel) and subtract the smaller area from the larger area.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
          </p>


          <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the following probabilities for a standard normal distribution:
                </p>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>P(Z\lt-0.5)</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p> In Excel:
                            <m>=NORM.S.DIST(-0.5,TRUE)\approx 0.3085 </m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>P(Z\gt 2.1)</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p> In Excel:
                            <m>=1-NORM.S.DIST(2.1,TRUE)\approx 0.0179 </m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>P(0.2\leq Z\leq 2.7)</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p> In Excel:
                            <m>=NORM.S.DIST(2.7,TRUE)-NORM.S.DIST(0.2,TRUE)\approx 0.4173 </m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>
            </statement>
          </example>


